            <div type="glosses">
                <note xml:id="VENUSGLOSS" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">&#x201C;proud <name type="astronomical" corresp="#VENUSPLANET">venus</name>&#x201D; 
                    (<title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>)&#x2014;</hi>Ruskin's epithet of <hi rend="italic">proud</hi> for Venus is not typical; 
                    in poetry, Venus is more commonly admired for its beauty than for its pride. In volume 2, "On Astronomy", 
                    of Scientific Dialogues by Jeremiah Joyce, the Tutor begins the conversation, "Of Venus", 
                    by glossing "the most beautiful" of planets with Milton's hymn to the Creator's "glorious works" 
                    in Paradise Lost:</p>
                    <floatingText>
                        <body>
                            <div type="poem">
                                <lg type="blank_verse">
                                    <l>Fairest of Stars, last in the train of Night</l>
                                    <l>If better thou belong not to the dawn,</l>
                                    <l>Sure pledge of day, that crown'st the smiling Morn</l>
                                    <l>With thy bright Circlet, praise him in thy Sphere</l>
                                    <l>While day arises, that sweet hour of Prime.</l>
                                </lg>
                            </div>
                            <div type="prose">
                                <p>(bk. 5, lines 166-70, in Milton, <hi rend="italic">Complete Poems and Major Prose</hi>, ed. Hughes, 306)</p>
                            </div>
                        </body>
                    </floatingText>
                    <p>The tutor goes on to explain how Venus's appearance as the "Evening Star" is defined by its position east of the sun, 
                        and as the "Morning Star" by its position west of the sun--appearances that arise from the planet's orbit as viewed from the Earth. 
                        To illustrate these more scientific astronomical observations, the Tutor turns to lines from The Excursion (1728; bk. 2, lines 77-81) 
                        by David Mallet (1701/2-65) (Joyce, conversation 19, "Of Venus", in Scientific Dialogues, 2:198, 202).</p>
                </note>                

                <note xml:id="ORIONGLOSS" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">&#x201C;belt of <name type="astronomical" corresp="#ORION">orion</name>&#x201D; 
                    (<title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>)&#x2014;</hi>Orion the hunter wields a club in one hand and a lion skin as a shield in the other. 
                    His belt, the most noticeable feature of the constellation, is formed by three equidistant stars in a straight row. 
                    Situated south of Taurus (the Bull) and Gemini (the Twins, Castor and Pollux), which are constellations in the zodiac, 
                    Orion is situated below the ecliptic. In the northern hemisphere, therefore, it is visible low on the horizon in the winter evening 
                    (Green, Astronomical Recreations, 68). In Ruskin's geography text, "<hi rend="italic">Orion</hi>, containing his Sword and luminous Belt", is considered 
                    one of the "most remarkable" constellations "to the naked eye or telescope", along with "<hi rend="italic">Taurus</hi>, containing the Pleiades; 
                    and <hi rend="italic">Ursa Major</hi>, containing the <hi rend="italic">Pointers</hi> to the North Star: all visible in our winter evenings" 
                    (Goldsmith, Grammar of General Geography, 8).</p></note>

                <note xml:id="MARSGLOSS" resp="#DCH">p><hi rend="bold">&#x201C;red <name type="astronomical" corresp="#MARS">mars</name> . . . / On his throne&#x201D; 
                    (<title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>)&#x2014;</hi>The "dusky red appearance" of the planet Mars 
                    is commonly remarked (coversation 20, "Of Mars", in Joyce, Scientific Dialogues, 2:207). The iconography of seating 
                    the Olympian gods on thrones may have been most familiar to Ruskin from the synod of the gods in book 15 of Homer's Iliad 
                    (in Pope's translation), after Jupiter has rebuked Juno for assisting the Trojans. Juno provokes Mars to resentful rage 
                    for the loss of his son, Ascalaphus. Minerva "[s]tarts from her azure throne to calm the god", reminding him of the futility 
                    of striving against Jove, and "[t]his menace fix'd the warrior to his throne; / Sullen he sat, and curb'd the rising groan" 
                    (bk. 15, lines 141, 160-61). This passage also pertains to the association of Mars and Venus, Juno having conspired with Venus in book 14 
                    to distract Jupiter from the battlefield with love-making and sleep 
                    (Homer, Iliad, trans. Pope, 307, and see 303-7, 292-97). For Ruskin's 1824 edition of Pope's Iliad, see 
                    <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="boyhood_books_note.php#DESCRIPTIONS">Books Used by Ruskin in His Youth: Physical Descriptions</ref>.</note>

